<section class="faq-section">
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q">What is the difference between SKU and barcode?</div>
<div class="faq-a">A barcode (UPC/EAN) is a universal product identifier assigned by GS1 and recognized globally. A SKU is an internal code created by the seller or warehouse operator for inventory tracking purposes. Barcodes identify the product universally, while SKUs identify the product within your specific system, often encoding information like color, size, and warehouse location.</div>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q">How many characters should a good SKU have?</div>
<div class="faq-a">An effective SKU typically has 8-12 characters. Shorter codes are easier for warehouse staff to read and type, while longer codes can encode more information. Avoid exceeding 16 characters as it increases error rates during manual handling. Use a combination of letters and numbers, but avoid characters that look similar like O and 0 or I and 1.</div>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q">Can a fulfillment center manage SKUs for me?</div>
<div class="faq-a">Yes. Professional fulfillment operators like MTP Group can create and manage your entire SKU architecture. During onboarding, your products are mapped to unique identifiers in the warehouse management system. The fulfillment center handles barcode labeling, location assignment, and inventory tracking, so you can focus on sales and marketing.</div>
</div>
</section>


